Last minute: our cosmic visitor is the giant asteroid 2014 JO25
There are billions, perhaps more, of giant asteroids roaming the solar system that could have serious consequences if they collided.
These objects, which can have closed or open orbits left over from the formation of the Sun, sometimes pass through Earth.
The 650-meter-diameter asteroid 2014 JO25 is one such visitor, and today at 14:24 it will pass 1.75 million kilometers from its closest position to Earth.
We're hearing more and more of this kind of news every day.
The main reason for this is the advancement in observation techniques and instruments.
This allows us to detect smaller asteroids that we couldn't detect before.
For example, last January an asteroid the size of a bus passed within half the distance of Earth and the Moon.
And even more interesting, the asteroid was detected just days before the transit.
So there could be other space buses coming at us right now.
Imagine if you were told that an asteroid 20 meters in diameter was about to hit your neighborhood.
Asteroids this size won't actually destroy your neighborhood, but they'll probably blow the windows off all the buildings.
This will be due to the shock waves from the asteroid that will explode in the atmosphere.
For example, the asteroid that hit Russia in 2013 was this size, and it was enough to smash the windows of buildings in several cities.
But if you have a neighborhood within 100 meters of an asteroid, you should go at least 50 kilometers beyond your recommended neighborhood.
Criteria such as the size of the asteroid and the angle of impact are the factors that determine the depth of the crater that will form and the damage that will be caused by the impact.
Let's look at a few scenarios based on the European Space Agency's simulation.
If an asteroid 100 meters in diameter hits the Earth at a 45-degree angle, at 60 kilometers per second, it will form a crater about 250 meters deep and with an arch of 1,200 meters.
The impact is equivalent to a magnitude 6 earthquake on the Richter scale, and even if you're 10 kilometers from the point of impact, you'll have a third-degree burn.
The others, 50 kilometers away, will be waiting for broken windows.
If it hits an asteroid one kilometer in diameter, it's even more dismal.
If such an asteroid hit the Earth at the same angle and speed, it would form a crater about 600 meters deep and 12 kilometers in diameter.
So a whole neighborhood turns into a crater and disappears instantly.
The heat from the impact causes a third-degree burn to your body even if you're 100 kilometers from the point of impact.
The impact is equivalent to an earthquake of magnitude 8 on the Richter scale.
The damage from the asteroid depends not only on the chemical composition of the asteroid but also on the rock structure of the area it will hit.
The above values are given in reference to the scenario that would occur if a rock-like asteroid fell into a region of clumpy rocks.
If the asteroid is mostly iron, and it falls on a surface formed by the cooling of lava, the crater will triple in size, and the resulting catastrophe will be doubled.
66 million years ago, the dinosaurs were hit worse, and were devastated by an asteroid about 10 kilometers across.
The asteroid impact wiped out 75 percent of all marine and land life in an instant.
If an asteroid this size is targeting Earth, which is destroying the dinosaurs, I'm sure the safest option would be to leave the planet.
Tonnes of matter falling from space to Earth every day.
Most of it burns up in the atmosphere.
Some meteorites that are large enough burn up in the atmosphere, causing flares known to the public as stellar slips.
Let's end our summer with another piece of good news.
Studies show that no massive asteroid is expected to hit Earth in the next 300 to 400 years, causing major destruction.
As creatures that live an average of 70 years, I'm sure you're relieved.
