Human rights group issues travel advisory for Missouri
The National Association for the Advancement of Colored People issued a warning for people of color to travel to Missouri because of the state's discriminatory policies and racist attacks.
The group's statement reads: "The Missouri NAACP Travel Advisory Notice, effective August 28, 2017, urges African American travelers, visitors, and Missourians to exercise extreme caution and caution when traveling statewide as noted there, due to the recent suspicious, racially-based incidents occurring statewide".
The NAACP said a new Missouri law makes it harder for people to win discrimination lawsuits, and that the disproportionate targeting of minorities by state law enforcement was instrumental in the group's issuance of this travel warning.
"There are human rights violations that people have.
They're being stopped, beaten and killed because of the color of their skin", Rod Chapel, president of the Missouri NAACP, told the Kansas City Star.
"We're hearing complaints at a rate we've never heard before".
This is the first time the Association has issued a warning for a state in the United States.
The group cited the incidents of racist insults against black students at the University of Missouri and the death of Tory Sanders, a black man from Tennessee.
Sanders was detained by Missouri police earlier this year without charge, after running out of gas while crossing the state, and died under suspicious circumstances.
The advisory also highlights a new report from the Missouri Attorney General's Office that states that black drivers are 75 percent more likely to be stopped than whites.
"The advisory is for people to be alert and alert their families, friends and coworkers to the possibility of being in Missouri", Chapel said.
"People should be ready to bring bail money, to inform their relatives that they will pass through this state".
Missouri had 100 hate crimes in 2015, according to the latest figures from the FBI's hate crime reporting program, which ranks the state 16th in the nation for the number of similar violations.
The travel warning is also in response to a new Missouri law that makes it harder for a business to sue for discrimination when renting a home or hiring.
The American Civil Liberties Union (ACLU) previously issued travel advisories for Texas and Arizona after those states passed immigration enforcement laws mandating that local law enforcement authorities arrest people for immigration violations; the ACLU says this will increase enforcement based on race.
Travel warnings are usually issued by the State Department for other countries, but recently advocacy groups have resorted to this practice in response to a number of laws and trends within the United States.
