Blocking critics on Facebook: If you can't remove voters' criticism, don't run for public office
The father of our country had some knowledge of negative press.
Americans loved George Washington, but it wasn't long before the newspapers began to harshly criticize him about everything from domestic politics to his political principles.
Of course, he was upset by the criticism.
But he did not silence his critics.
Because in 1783, Washington said, "Freedom of speech can be abolished and we can be led to slaughter in a stupid and silent way".
Which brings me to Maryland Governor Larry Hogan, who needs to work harder to be like Washington.
Hogan's staff blocked and deleted the posts of at least 450 people who expressed their views on his official Facebook page.
The American Civil Liberties Union sued him earlier this week.
The governor's staff ignored the case on the grounds that it was minor, and online comments were filled with "who cares?" reactions.
A lot of people said, "It's just Facebook".
But it's important.
Especially when it's someone like Hogan.
This is a Republican governor who is surprisingly popular in a state where the oppressor is a predominantly Democrat.
He has the second highest approval rating of any of the 50 governors in the country.
Hogan is not a reactionary firecracker.
He was a master at leading his province and a staunch believer in principles.
He was also quite adept at using Facebook as his primary tool to connect with his constituents, with his humorous presentation of his hairless post-chemotherapy head.
So blocking people from visiting the governor's page, which is a public forum, officially certified and run by staff members who pay the people's tax dollars, is unnecessary and ultimately dangerous.
In an interview with The Washington Post, Hogan's female spokeswoman Amelia Chasse defended the governor's actions, claiming that blocking comments was nothing more than editing them.
But it's easy to use images of trolls or spammers or hateful people doing online verbal attacks.
The Post spoke to some of the actual people who were blocked by Hogan.
And these are just real people talking to their elected leaders: a teacher, a business owner, and a priest; not trolls.
They all said that his comments were not respectful, considerate, and blasphemous.
The pastor shared a quote from the Bible, referring to Hogan's Catholic faith.
Lawyer Lakshmi Sarma Ramani from Bowie, Maryland, was not hateful but asked about hate crimes.
He wrote in the Post's comment section of the story, "I have made a subtle comment that I am disappointed by his lack of response to hate crimes and other recent news".
"I also don't like the idea that when so many people are commenting on the same issue, it's just a big group of concerned citizens, rather than some, who are ignoring it as a collective effort".
What the governor's staff called a "focused spam attack" will probably be called "advocacy" by others.
The Facebook era makes it easy to make a message easily relevant by blocking an opponent or deleting a negative message.
Much cleaner than the old days when staff were sent out to collect and burn newspapers with critical articles or to arrest and silence protesters.
But, even if it's digital, that's exactly what's happening.
Hogan isn't the first public official to be criticized for disabling Facebook and other social media.
President Trump is being sued by Twitter users who have been blocked from their Twitter feed.
One of the decisions that could be a reference in the future on this issue came from Virginia last week.
The Loudoun County Board of Supervisors chairman violated the First Amendment when he banned a poll on Facebook, according to U.S. District Judge James C. Cacheris in Alexandria.
In Kentucky, Governor Matt Bevin (R-C) was visited by the ACLU for his use of Facebook and Twitter.
It shouldn't be that hard.
In Washington's time, the era of affordable mail had a similar effect to the Internet.
Between 1775 and 1800, newspapers quadrupled in number, and anonymous letter writers eroded his leadership.
Even then, Washington had its unnamed trolls.
People using the aliases "Juricola", "Valerius", "Belisarius", and "Portius" all wrote letters to the newspapers denouncing Washington's decisions.
According to the online historical document collection Project, the George Washington Papers, the office was overwhelmed by petitions criticizing his handling of the Treaty of Amity, Commerce and Navigation with Britain.
But he didn't shut them up.
Freedom of speech, freedom of dissent and freedom of association are at the heart of our nation.
And true leadership is about accepting that.
