An existing movement that was propagandizing independence against Dutch rule quickly turned its anger to the Jakarta government, which maintained tight control over the region, banning foreign journalists or rights watchdog organizations.
In 2003, the territory was officially split into Papua and West Papua, with independent Papua New Guinea occupying the eastern part of the island.
Enarotali is as remote as it is deserted; the journey here involves a 90-minute flight from the regional capital of Jayapura to Nabire and a five-hour belly-wiggling drive in a rented car.
No public transportation.
The 19,000-person township includes wooden houses surrounded by bamboo fences, wrinkled iron roofs turned to various yellowish-brown tones by rust.
Let alone journalists, very few Indonesians have traveled here and almost no foreigners have traveled here.
Before the Christian missionaries arrived, the Mee Pago worshipped a god called Uga Tamee.
There have been other changes.
"We weren't used to wearing these clothes", she says, referring to her brightly colored, hand-touched yellow, dark shirt and glossy skirt.
"We used to wear only leaves on our bodies".
Papua is the poorest region of Indonesia, with 28 percent of the population living below the poverty line and the worst infant mortality and literacy rates in Asia.
But it's also the golden land of Indonesia.
Grasberg, the world's largest and most profitable gold mine owned by Phoenix-based Freeport McMoran, is located just 60 miles from Paniai, a mountainous region the size of New Jersey and home to 153,000 people.
In 2015 alone, Freeport extracted approximately $3.1 billion worth of gold and copper from here.
In addition, Papua has an estimated $78 billion in timber reserves.
Yet, the wealth that is a source of misery for the Papuans keeps Indonesia's mighty military alive.
A 2005 New York Times study reports that Freeport paid nearly $20 million to local military personnel and units between 1998 and 2004, including payments of up to $150,000 to a single officer.
The Papuan call for greater autonomy threatens this golden egg-laying hen and its rights are ruthlessly denied.
Since 1969, rights advocates say, more than 500,000 Papuans have been killed by the Indonesian military, and thousands more have been raped, tortured, and imprisoned.
In the mountainous parts of Papua, mass killings in the 1970s have reached genocidal numbers, according to the Asian Commission on Human Rights.
Indonesian police arrested more than 3,900 peaceful protesters in the region last year alone.
The 2016 "We Will Lose Everything" report from the Archdiocese of Brisbane includes table witness accounts of the previous year's unlawful executions, torture (according to another report, rape and electrocution are particularly popular), and the brutal suppression of peaceful demonstrations.
"It is difficult to count the number of victims because there are incidents every week", says Andreas Harsono, an Indonesian researcher at Human Rights Watch.
As Papua's resources brought in settlers from other parts of Indonesia, pressure was heightened.
The region's population of 3.5 million is 83% Christian, but the demographics are changing as Muslim immigrants from Indonesia's populous islands of Java, Borneo, Sumatra and Sulawesi arrive for economic purposes.
They sell gado-gado, served with chicken and vegetable mixed with peanut sauce.
The locals are struggling to compete.
"The migrants sell chicken and vegetables at traditional markets at a lower price than the indigenous Papuans", explains Abeth You, a 24-year-old Paniai native who moved to the regional capital, Jayapura, for work.
"This has caused the indigenous Papuans, the Papuans' mama-mama (women), to lose market share".
Indonesian President Joko Widodo, better known as Jokowi, vowed to address inequality and rights abuses in Papua during his 2014 election campaign.
The former carpenter, on his way to the presidential palace in Jakarta, took the game of 27 of Papua's 29 provinces, including Panaia.
But little has changed in Papua, and today the locals feel cheated.
"We are heartbroken because in 2014 we voted for Jokowi, expecting him to fulfill our hope that justice will be restored", You said.
In fact, Paniai experienced his worst condition just two months after Jokowi took office in October.
On December 7, 2014, a group of 11 children were out singing Christmas carols in front of a bonfire in Enarotali, and two Indonesian soldiers on motorbikes passed through the darkness.
The frightened kids told them to turn on their lights.
One of the soldiers resented their style, and according to local priest Yavedt Tebai, he later returned with four soldiers.
Victims and witnesses said that soldiers, who were drunk, chased the group and beat them with the tips of their rifles.
Then one of the soldiers shot at the group of children.
One of the boys, 16-year-old Yulianus Yeimo, was so badly beaten that he slipped into a coma.
A few hours later, the nearby government election commission building was set on fire, and the next day, the situation escalated.
About 1,000 Papuan men, women and children gathered at a football field in front of the local police station and military command center to demand justice.
They carried ceremonial hunting bows and performed the waita dance of the Mee Pago tribe of Papua (running in a ring and imitating the song of birds).
Some protesters started throwing stones at the police and military garrison.
As tensions mounted, orders were sent to the soldiers over the internal radio: "If the crowd shows more than three times resistance, shoot them".
Jeremiah Kayame, 56, the mayor of Kego Koto neighborhood in Enarotali, saw the danger approaching and pleaded with the crowd to return home and demand calm.
No one was listening.
"When I turned around, I was shot in the left wrist", he told TIME while presenting his brightly painted wooden house.
Kayame still doesn't know who fired the shot but says the bullet came from a military meltdown
"There was a crowd, multiple shots fired", he adds.
According to his cousin, Alfius Youw, who witnessed the attacks, he was shot three times.
"I ran to him and examined his body to make sure it was him", Yohan, who, like many Indonesians, is known only by his first name, told TIME in a somber tone.
"I saw him die... and I kissed him".
Papua Police Chief Inspector General Yotje Mende told reporters that his officers were only "securing" the police station because it was under attack.
Papua police spokesman Branch Chief Pudjo Sulistiyo said in 2015: "When people threaten to kill us, we have to defend ourselves".
"This is a matter of life and death".
According to Human Rights Watch, five young protesters were killed and many more were injured.
News of the deaths reached Jakarta only the next day.
Jokowi gave a passionate speech in Jayapura three weeks later, expressing his sympathy for the families of the victims and promising to address the historic abuses in Papua.
"I want this case resolved immediately so that it doesn't happen again".
In October 2016, Minister of Security Wiranto said that he had set up a non-judicial mechanism for historic human rights violations.
But the excuses started almost immediately.
"Most of the breaches were long ago.
Some in the '90s, some in the early 2000s.
The point is, we are determined to solve these violations, but there are processes that we have to go through".
Speaking to TIME on June 5, Wiranto backtracked, saying there were no plans to set up a complaints mechanism in Papua.
Instead, he said, "It's all going to be decided by the law".
Wiranto, who accused B.M. of "crimes against humanity" related to the deaths of more than 1,000 people during East Timor's bloody independence vote in 1999, said 11 human rights violations in Papua had already been solved, including the Paniai incident.
The families of the victims of Paniai have met such claims with bitter suspicion.
"I have been invited four times in the past three years, but no progress has been made", says Yohanes.
I'm tired of it.
He says he's still living in fear, years later.
He says, "I'm scared".
"I'm afraid of being arrested by the military, I'm afraid of being shot".
His brother Yacobus reiterates his view that the people of Paniai are afraid to discuss the matter.
He says he was beaten by the soldier after helping bury four of the victims.
"After the bodies were buried, the soldier came looking for me", he says.
The attacks haven't stopped yet.
On Tuesday, Indonesian police opened fire on villagers in Deiyai, a neighbourhood of Paniai.
One person was killed and 17 people, including children, were injured during a clash between villagers and the manager of a construction company who refused to help take an unconscious man to hospital.
Ravianus Douw, 24, drowned in a nearby lake while fishing and died en route to the hospital.
Angry villagers protested outside the company's construction office.
Police said the villagers threw stones at the officers, who responded with warning shots.
But locals say the mobile brigade (Indonesian paramilitary police) opened fire on the crowd and killed one person.
"We were in a panic, afraid of retaliation", said 29-year-old Dominggu Badii, who lives near the hospital and witnessed the wounded being raised.
"I've been hiding in my house for two days".
The Deiyai parliament has called for the officials involved in this to be held accountable and for the mobile police brigade to be withdrawn from the area.
Paniai has always been a troubled area for the Indonesian government.
The lack of meaningful development has fueled the discontent of the Mee, Moni, Dani and Damal tribal peoples scattered throughout Papua's verdant highlands.
Many joined the rebel army Free Papua Movement (OPM), which claimed to protect the rights of Papuans by carrying out random attacks and kidnapping raids on Indonesian soldiers.
Some of the top OPM leaders, including Tadius Yogi and Daniel Judas Kogoya, are coming from Paniai.
In response, thousands of people in Paniai were arrested and arbitrarily detained by the military in recent years under the guise of "protecting national sovereignty".
Some are never seen again.
Among the people of Papua, Paniai is known as "a tragic and forgotten place".
Poverty feeds discontent.
The little rice that is on sale in Enarotali is too expensive for the natives to buy.
Bread is out of reach.
People here grow everything they eat: mostly nutmeg, as well as some fruits and leafy vegetables.
Farming is the work of women who can sustain four or five fields of sweet potatoes.
They usually keep most of the harvest for the family, selling the rest at the local market.
10 notes are only 10,000 Indonesian rupees (75 cents).
Over time, economic inequalities between the indigenous Papuans and the new immigrants arriving in greater numbers at Nabire Airport have grown since the opening of new air routes.
The jobs that are already scarce often go to the more educated and wealthier immigrants.
The Papuan people rarely have the capital or the skills to run their own business competitively.
"Young people are not interested in staying in the village because there is no work or money", says John Gobai, chairman of the Panai Tribal Council.
Isolation keeps the world's eyes off Papua.
In addition, there are strict restrictions on international media coverage.
Earlier this year, French journalists Franck Escudie and Basille Longchamp were deported from Papua for "lack of coordination with relevant agencies", despite the rare video-making permits they were given.
According to Phelim Kine, the deputy director of Human Rights Watch Asia, Jokowi's campaign promises to lift restrictions on news coverage and improve transparency have not been fulfilled.
In a statement, he said: "There are new dangers for foreign journalists covering Papua and West Papua, Indonesia's troubled eastern provinces: visa denial and blacklisting".
The lack of press control means that international pressure on the Indonesian government is largely confined to Papua's immediate neighbors.
On March 6, the Pacific nation (Tonga, Nauru, Palau, Tuvalu, Marshall Islands and Solomon Islands) urged the UN Human Rights Council to investigate "varied and widespread violations" in Papua, including the Panaia attacks.
The same countries have historically supported the OPM.
Indonesian Foreign Ministry spokesman Arrmanatha Nasir dismissed the group's claims, telling reporters in Jakarta that "the democratic system is still in place in Indonesia and there is a free media so it is difficult to cover up evidence in human rights cases".
The locals want more foreign government involvement.
When an official delegation from the Netherlands, led by the country's human rights ambassador Kees Van Baar, visited Jayapura on May 4, the local people broke their silence with pleas for "freedom", according to a source who attended the meeting and did not want to be named.
Indonesia has another presidential election in 2019, but the Papuans say it is unlikely that they will vote for Jokowi again.
"Jokowi is a well-meaning man, but he is surrounded by people who were involved in the Paniai attack", says tribal council president Gobai.
Jokowi wants the people of Paniai to know that they are living in a miserable state with scarce education and health care, in addition to the imminent threat of a tyrannical army.
Gobai says that the Paniai, like other Papuans, see their vote as a "debt" to Jokowi to pay back.
"They don't need money, they just want justice", he says.
Despite threats and intimidation, the families of the victims of the Paniai attack carried out a final symbolic act of resistance: burying the body of a victim in the field directly opposite the police and military station.
Knowing that justice may never be served, they will at least ensure that those responsible do not forget their crimes.
"A member of our family has been killed", says Yacobus, his head tilted forward.
"What else can we do?"
