The good news of 'social assistance' to more than 4 thousand chronic patients
The social assistance program, which will be launched for poor citizens and their families who are struggling with chronic diseases, according to the Ministry of Family and Social Policies, will benefit 4,300 tuberculosis and SSPE patients in the first phase.
The Ministry, which plans to provide patients with a monthly allowance of more than two-thirds of the minimum wage, will also provide regular psychosocial support.
According to the information received, details and principles of implementation of the "New Social Assistance Program for Families Struggling with Chronic Diseases" were revealed.
The social assistance program, which was launched in cooperation with the Ministry of Health to support citizens who are struggling with chronic diseases and are experiencing economic and psychological difficulties, is in many ways a first in the world.
The Ministry, which has completed all the necessary preparations for the launch of the program, will provide the families with a social assistance program, not only cash but also regular psychosocial support.
The aim is to ensure that the poor citizens and their families who have chronic diseases and continue their treatment process at home are not left alone, both financially and spiritually.
According to the studies, in the first phase, the new social assistance program will provide regular psychosocial and cash support to poor citizens who are battling tuberculosis and Sub-Acute Sclerosing Panencephaly (SSPE), a brain disease caused by the measles virus.
In the later stages of the program, poor citizens who are struggling with other rare and high-risk diseases will be included in the assistance program.
In addition to the support planned to be provided at a rate of more than two-thirds of the minimum wage, additional payments will be made to tuberculosis patients who are unable to afford medical care, are bed-dependent or are identified by the health department as in need of improvement of their home living conditions.
