EPA President Pruitt has given up on delaying Obama-era emissions cuts.
A day after being sued by 15 states, Environmental Protection Agency President Scott Pruitt reversed his decision to delay the implementation of previous Obama-era laws that reduced emissions of air pollutants that cause smog.
Pruitt represented a change in his organization's response to the needs of state environmental regulators, which was more responsive than previous administrations.
He never mentioned the legal challenge to his previous position in a federal high court.
It's about the states starting to meet the 2015 deadline for ground-level ozone standards, October 1.
Pruitt announced in June that he would delay compliance for a year to give his organization more time to work on the plan and to avoid "interfering with local decisions or hindering economic growth".
Pruitt, who was Oklahoma's attorney general before being appointed by President Donald Trump, had long served as a reliable ally against tighter environmental regulations.
Since arriving in Washington, Pruitt has repeatedly moved to block or delay regulations that the chemical and fossil fuel industries oppose.
Wednesday's sudden change is the latest legal defeat for Pruitt's reversal agenda.
Last month, a federal high court in Washington ruled that the EPA administrator's attempt to delay the implementation of an Obama administration law requiring oil and gas companies to monitor and reduce methane leaks was an overreach of his authority.
In a statement released Wednesday evening, Pruitt argued that the rollback in ozone standards only reinforces the EPA's commitment to working with states to meet new standards in a timely manner and through complex processes.
Pruitt, who sued the EPA more than a dozen times in his previous job, said: "Under previous administrations, the EPA often failed to meet deadlines for decisions, waited for activist groups and others to sue, and agreed on dispute resolution to set timelines for decisions".
"We don't believe in settlement by litigation, and we take term dates seriously.
We also take the law and the authority it gives us seriously".
However, the EPA's statement noted that Pruitt could once again use its "delay authority and all other authority legally available" at some point to ensure that the regulations are "backed by sound policies and the best available information".
Republicans in Congress are pushing for a broader rewrite of the ozone laws.
A House bill passed last month seeks to delay the implementation of the 2015 laws by at least eight years.
The measure has not yet been brought to a vote in the Senate.
New York Attorney General Eric Schneiderman, who led the coalition of states suing the EPA this week, said the group intends to continue the legal push.
Schneiderman said, "The EPA's decision to change its decision following our lawsuits is a significant victory for the health and safety of 6.7 million New Yorkers and more than 115 million Americans who are directly affected by the smog that flows into their communities".
The lawsuit was filed in New York from California, Connecticut, Delaware, Illinois, Iowa, Maine, Massachusetts, Minnesota, New Mexico, Oregon, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, Vermont, and Washington and the District of Columbia.
Ground-level ozone is produced when general pollutants are emitted from automobiles, power plants, oil refineries, chemical plants, and other sources that react to sunlight in the atmosphere.
The foul smoke emitted can cause serious respiratory problems in a group of people who are easily affected and contributes to thousands of premature deaths each year.
Public health advocates and environmentalists applauded Pruitt's surprise decision change.
"It's disturbing that so much pressure is needed from the person responsible for protecting the air we breathe to get this sensible step", said Lori Ann Burd of the Center for Biological Diversity.
"We must continue to fight the Trump administration's ideological struggle to exploit polluters and interest groups".
