Moore's Ford Massacre: Activists Revive the Racist Lynch for Justice
A 1948 Ford Mercury, Monroe, passed through a group of spectators in rural Georgia and made its way crawling towards the little Ford Bridge in Moore.
The car, with four black passengers and a white driver, was blocked by a group of armed white men before they reached the bridge.
The gang leader, a middle-aged man in a thin striped suit, took a long breath from his cigar and looked carefully through the windshield.
Inside, the people were trembling with fear.
"We want this shit, Roger!" he barked.
"Get him out of the car!"
Screams were heard through the darkness as a young black man was dragged from the front passenger seat.
Fortunately, this terrible scene of June 22nd is only a reenactment.
But when a ruler was thrown around "Roger's" neck, almost everyone in the audience breathed a very realistic sigh.
Since 2005, human rights activists have been returning to the Ford Bridge in Moore to reenact the lynching of two black couples (Roger and Dorothy Malcom and George and Mae Murray Dorsey) by the Ku Klux Klan in 1946.
So far, no one has been charged with the murders.
Tyrone Brooks, who helped organize the revival, said: "It's amazing that not a single person has been arrested over the years, even though we see them in our communities, even though we know who they are".
"It is a stain on history but a burden on our souls".
Brooks is a 71-year-old former Georgia state congressman and a lifelong human rights activist.
For him, this revival is a dramatic call to action and an annual reminder to Monroe's community that an injustice has never been rectified.
