But one of them was never investigated.
While the suspects remained fugitives for decades, human rights activists say the twin motives of lynchings have always been well known throughout the town: politics and sex.
In April 1946, a high court ruling allowed black citizens in Georgia to vote for the first time in a primary election later that summer.
At about the same time as the election, according to the FBI, his black partner Roger Malcom stabbed Barnett Hester, a white landowner, during a fight apparently involving a woman.
Brooks stated that the town rumor was that Hester slept with Malcolm's wife Dorothy and that the baby she was carrying was not from her husband.
According to the FBI, on July 25, 1946, a prominent white landowner named Loy Harrison paid $600 to get Malcolm out of prison.
Dorothy and her cousins Mae Murray and George Dorsey went to prison with her.
