The latest results of a new medical age assessment test for refugees in Sweden found that more than 80 percent of the participants were over the age of 18, but not everyone is confident in the accuracy of the tests.
Sweden's national Forensic Medicine and Medicines Agency (Rättsmedicinalverket) started testing earlier this year.
The tests were designed to make the age assessment in the asylum process more accurate after the Swedish Migration Agency (Migrationsverket) criticized the failure of some refugees who claimed to be underage to assess their age correctly.
To date, Migrationsverket has sent 6880 cases to the test and the Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceuticals Department has now released the results of 2481 of the tests from mid-March to 31 July 2017.
Eighty percent (out of 2002) were judged to be 18 or over, and in 25 cases the Office of Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceuticals ruled that the subject was "probably 18 and over".
In 432 cases, the result was that the person was "probably under 18".
Tests were only done in cases where the person's age was suspected.
Johan Göransson from the Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceutical Department says the results are consistent with the past few months.
He told The Local, "We don't see a big difference in the statistics from the previous months, the numbers are pretty consistent".
The high rate of cases that are judged to be over 18 does not necessarily mean that refugees are lying about their age.
In May, the department released the results of 581 tests, and said there were 442 cases "in which the subjects examined were shown to be 18 years of age or older".
When the newspaper Svenska Dagbladet reviewed the results of 581 cases reported, it found that 243 cases openly stated that they had turned 18 this year.
The medical age assessment method, which involves taking X-rays of 20-year-old teeth and MRI scans of knee joints, and then having them analyzed by dentists and radiologists, is criticized in some circles.
One skeptic is Karolinska Institute endocrinologist Claude Marcus, who has been studying the biological maturity of humans to determine whether they enter puberty earlier or later than normal.
"I have reasons to think about it, and I think that this is not the kind of measurement that should be used.
It's very questionable to judge biological age in this way.
If we can't say for sure, we shouldn't pretend to be", he told Metro.
However, Göransson of the Forensic Medicine and Pharmaceuticals Department defended the accuracy of the tests: "You can say that the risk of a child being misjudged as an adult is generally small.
The greatest risk is that the person is just under 18, and in this case the risk is about 10 percent".
