After a battle in the High Court over the funding of the drug in the NHS, patients will be able to access 'transformative' HIV prevention treatment from September.
NHS England announced that pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP), a pill taken before sex, will be provided by health services to approximately 10,000 people through a three-year pre-trial, which has been shown to reduce the risk of infection by around 86 per cent in high-risk individuals.
The Supreme Court's decision last year agreed to fund the trial after the Court of Appeal upheld the decision, saying the NHS had the power to pay for PrEP despite local authorities' claims to fund it.
The move, announced on Thursday, was hailed as a "new and serious intervention" by Simon Stevens, head of NHS England, while the National Aids Trust (NAT) described it as a "turning point".
Sexual health clinics in London, Brighton, Manchester, Liverpool and Sheffield will be public first-choice clinics, with more clinics joining in October and fully implemented across the UK by April 2018.
Pre-exposure prophylaxis (PrEP) is a series of HIV medications that reduce the risk of contracting HIV before sex.
Trials have shown that PrEP significantly reduces HIV transmission among those at risk of infection.
Taking PrEP before sex means that a person has enough of the drugs in his body to prevent HIV from settling in.
These drugs can be taken every day or up to two hours before sex.
Those eligible for treatment are gay or bisexual men, transgender people, and HIV-positive partners who are not successfully treated.
Clinics will identify suitable participants from men, women, transgender individuals, and those whose partners' HIV status is unknown to be controlled by an antiretroviral therapy.
People living in the UK and registered with a practitioner will also be able to register for potential participation in participating local sexual health clinics.
The programme will cost £10 million and NHS England has signed an agreement to supply the drugs this week in an international tender.
The trial is designed to assess the full potential of PrEP by collecting clinical evidence on how PrEP is targeted, implemented and implemented at large scale.
Mr Stevens said: 'This new and serious intervention will contribute to the widespread and increasingly successful efforts to prevent HIV.
This is another milestone in thirty years of progress toward solving one of mankind's major health problems.'
Deborah Gold, president of the National Aids Trust, said: 'This is a turning point in the fight against HIV.
If PrEP is properly targeted at those who need it and those at risk, it has the potential to turn the HIV epidemic in the UK around.
Starting in September, people at high risk of HIV will have access to a new and powerful tool, which is truly personalized and non-negotiable with a spouse, through this trial funded by the NHS in the UK, which will lead to the healing of many lives.
We are warmly welcoming this message.'
Ian Green, chairman of the Terrence Higgins Trust, said: 'The priority now is to ensure that the trial is rapidly rolled out nationwide and that no one at risk of HIV is left behind.
With the experimental drug PrEP now available, we are on track to protect more than 10,000 people at risk of HIV".
Shadow Public Health Minister Sharon Hodgson said: 'We welcome the start of the PrEP trial, and it has been delayed by months of delays and then government backlash.
The evidence shows how transformative this drug can be as part of our approach to preventing HIV and ending the spread of this life-changing infection.
The trial will bring us one step closer to fully understanding the benefits of PrEP.
Now it's important that this trial is rolled out nationwide as quickly as possible to protect those exposed to HIV and to bring us one step closer to ending the spread of HIV in our communities.
