The dinosaur used camouflage to avoid its enemies.
At first glance, it looks like a statue, but it's a terrible one.
Researchers now say that the first finds of an incredible creature the size of a rhinoceros, discovered by a Canadian miner, are so well preserved that experts have identified it as the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.
It was so well preserved that they could tell the stamp was reddish brown and could say it had a 'problematic past'.
A report in the journal Current Biology described it as 'the best preserved armored dinosaur and one of the best dinosaur breeds in the world.'
The fossil is a newly discovered species of nodosaur that lived from the middle of the Cretaceous period, 110 million to 112 million years ago.
Its remarkably well-preserved condition has baffled researchers who describe it as 'truly marvelous.'
The herbivore armored beetle is the best-preserved fossil of its kind, according to reports in National Geographic.
It was found by Shawn Funk on March 21, 2011, while digging the Suncor Millennium Mine near Fort McMurray in northern Alberta, Canada.
He hit something that looked strange from the surrounding rock, and decided to take a closer look.
The fossil was sent to the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
They spent the next six years extracting the wild animal from a 2,500-pound (1,100 kg) pile of soil.
After all this intense work, the finished result is now ready to be unveiled.
"If you close your eyes a little bit, you can even believe that it's almost asleep", says lead author Caleb Brown, a scientist at the Royal Tyrrell Museum, where the creature is on display.
'It will go down in the history of science as one of the most beautiful and best preserved dinosaur species, the Mona Lisa of dinosaurs.'
Researchers examined its skin and found that although it was covered in armor and looked like a walking tank, this herbivore was likely facing a serious threat from flesh-eating dinosaurs.
Heavily armoured, the dinosaur used red and white camouflage to hide from predators, and used a protective technique known as counter-shading, which is also used by many modern animals.
Experts suggest that it was hunted by larger dinosaurs, which allowed it to better blend into its environment and outrun its enemies.
The 110-million-year-old creature from the family of nodosaurs first made headlines in May and is now on display at the Royal Tyrrell Museum of Paleontology.
Now that the researchers had finished their work, they named the wild animal Borealopelta markmitchelli in honour of Mark Mitchell, a museum technician who was part of the team that spent over 7,000 painstaking hours to uncover it.
The remarkable preservation of the species has enabled Dr. Mitchell and his international team of scientists to document the pattern and shape of the seals and the armor on the body.
They discovered counter-shading, a common defense method in the animal kingdom, which means the upper part of the creature is darker on the underside.
Although counter-shading is common, the findings are surprising because the size of the Borealopelta far exceeds that of any of the counter-shading animals alive today.
This means that the dinosaur has been hunted enough by the meat-eating dinosaurs to prefer hiding to facing evolution as a method of survival.
But the most modern animals that use counter-shading -- such as deer, zebras, or armadillos -- are much smaller and much more prone to being prey, which means that this nodosaur faced a serious challenge in surviving.
'The intense hunting of a giant, heavily armored animal shows just how dangerous the dinosaur predators of the Cretaceous can be,' said Brown.
