How does an activist have to find out the answer to the question "Whose Streets?"
On August 9, 2014, Brittany Ferrell was deeply shaken.
The day after he arrived in New York City for a trip, the St. Louis native sat on the bed of his rented Airbnb and started surfing Facebook on his phone.
It just happened to be shared by someone in high school.
"The police just killed an 18-year-old boy, and he's still lying on the street".
When he realized that no one else had shared this information in the content stream, he was surprised, so he shut down Facebook and started Twitter.
A user nicknamed @TheePharoah was constantly retweeted in his content stream.
Rapper from the St. Louis area was tweeting live about the death of Michael Brown, who was killed at the age of 18 by an unarmed black, white police officer in Ferguson, Missouri.
He shared a photo of Brown's serial corpse in the street, which he's gonna be there for four hours.
Ferrell thought to himself, "This is brutal".
But death was not new to him or to his society.
He left his phone to return to tweets about the crowd on Canfield Drive later that evening.
There were police tapes, people screaming, and a man holding a sign that said, "Ferguson police just killed my unarmed son!"
He watched a live broadcast of a police officer standing in front of a group of protesters with a barking dog.
In another video, another cop, he said, pulled the trigger and shouted, "I'm gonna kill you all... animals".
Ferrell remembered saying, "This is unusual".
"'This is not a typical murder of the kind we are accustomed to.'
I felt a chill at that moment.
I was angry and I was crying".
He booked a return ticket and went home the next day.
After landing at 11 p.m., he picked up his 6-year-old daughter from her father's house and decided to take her to Ferguson the next morning.
What happened to Ferrell and Ferguson over the next three years is the subject of a new documentary coming to theaters on August 11 called "Whose Streets?"
It's a story of survival and protest, of love and loss, of power and resistance, told from the perspective of the people who live in that community and fill the streets with the answers they seek.
Ferrell drove to Ferguson with his daughter, who wore a floral dress and a matching crown, and they returned that morning to a conversation they had repeatedly had earlier, "about the experiences of black people and the condition of black people".
He remembered saying, "Remember when I taught you that black people should fight for what they believe in?"
"We're going to Ferguson right now because the police killed an 18-year-old boy and it wasn't true.
I couldn't help it".
"What is happening here today is a consequence of what happened in the past.
He's got to know it, see it, and grow into it.
It should not only be well-developed in activism and organizing, but it should also know the layers of the black experience and the black condition and what we need to do to liberate, to liberate ourselves.
Even if I'm lucky enough to give her an experience where she doesn't personally experience gross racism, she's no different than any black woman-child.
I feel that by protecting her from that, I am doing her harm".
When they arrived in Ferguson, their first stop was South Florissant Road, which had become a sort of campground for activists, opposite the police headquarters, where they waited for Officer Darren Wilson to speak about the matter, which later resulted in no criminal charges being brought.
There, Ferrell and her daughter made contact with local business owners who prepared packaged food.
They packed bags and helped deliver them to the protesters.
A new kind of activism was slowly forming for Ferrell.
While a student at Missouri State University, she was president of the Minority Student Nurses Association and focused on food justice and injustice in health care in the black community, noting, "My activism completely changed after August 9".
"I had no experience in organizing.
It just came out of nowhere".
Weeks later, Ferrell met with one of the film's co-directors, Sabaah Folayan, at an evening show.
Folayan said he and his own image director Lucas Alvarado-Farrar wanted to "document" what happened.
Ferrell had a question in his mind: "Do you want to document or do you want to find a story that you can use?"
This skepticism was expressed by countless individuals, mostly white, who came to a society to profit from its suffering and resistance.
As Folayan explained in a recent interview, "We heard that the voices of people who were born and raised in Ferguson couldn't concentrate, and we decided to do it differently".
Folayan had already made contact with co-director Damon Davis, a regional artist known for his activism on death row.
His involvement warmed Ferrell to the project, which the "Whose Streets?" team, along with six other area natives, followed in the years after Brown's shooting.
"This is not a documentary where someone speaks for us or speaks to us; we are the ones who speak", David said.
"That's what was important to me, how these people were going to be represented, because that's how I was going to be represented".
Folayan spoke in a way that "while the goal is not to focus on Ferrell's experiences, he proved to be the most open of film participants, showing that the movement is not about a "Messiah leader, it's about the community coming together".
As a result, "Whose Streets?" surprisingly documents personal aspects of Ferrell's life, such as his falling in love and marrying his wife.
Ferrell laughed at the first sight of the finished product, saying, "I felt like I was naked".
"But I realized that in doing this and humanizing black people, there might be some sensitivity".
And Ferrell's story reinforces and re-centers the role of black lesbian women in the Black Lives Matter movement.
Two of the three founders of the movement, who inspired the #BlackLivesMatter slogan on social media after the murder of a black teenager, Trayvon Martin, in 2012, identify as gay.
"Black lesbian women in leadership have generally kept the movement going", said Ferrell, "and that's because we're constantly at war on many fronts.
Black lesbian women have to carry the full weight of it".
Folayan added: "The movement is really being sustained by black women and many gay black women".
Yet Ferrell insists that "this is nothing of the sort of affirmative action" and that he was not chosen because of his identities.
"He was the one who set that energy in motion", she says.
"But it's no coincidence that she's on the front lines, because as a black lesbian woman, you have a lot to lose by living a life at these intersections.
You can feel his energy on the screen".
In Ferguson, meanwhile, the news cameras are long gone, but there are still disturbing racial connections between the community and the police.
Ferrell is on probation for another two and a half years for shutting down the highway during a demonstration.
The socio-political atmosphere in the area he calls home is, in one word, "confusion".
And yet, Ferguson still remembers the song he wrote three years before he took to the streets.
"It is our duty to fight for our freedom.
It's our job to win.
We should love and support each other.
We have nothing to lose but our chains".
