A relevant parallel: The artist uses Chelsea Manning's DNA to create portraits
In the middle of the room in the New York Fridman Gallery, there are many faces, white, black, and brown, hanging over cables in the ceiling, each with an almost indistinct resemblance to the other.
These 30 portraits were created by artist Heather Dewey-Hagborg, using earrings and haircuts sent to her by Chelsea Manning.
Former intelligence analyst Manning, who is serving a 35-year sentence for leaking classified diplomatic messages through the WikiLeaks channel, has sent his haircut from Fort Leavenworth prison.
The new exhibition, which opens on August 2, is called A Matching Similarity.
It's the product of two years of correspondence between Dewey-Hagborg, who combines her discipline with her expertise in technology, computer science and art, and Manning, a trans woman and leading opponent who was pardoned by Barack Obama three days before her term expired.
By algorithmically analyzing the DNA extracted from Manning and creating 30 portraits of what a person with this gene data might look like, Dewey-Hagborg not only revealed the processing of the DNA data (there are many ways to be named and the inherent determinism of interpretations) but also revealed its identity with a tight, perhaps somewhat cerebral interpretation.
Manning, who was born Edward Bradley but openly identified as a woman in his later teens, was convicted in 2013 of 20 counts, including six under the Espionage Act, computer fraud and theft.
His image was suppressed by the prison, so that there was only one photograph: a black-and-white photo of Manning, visibly agitated, sitting in the driver's seat, wearing a platinum-yellow wig that resonated with him.
In 2015, Dewey-Hagborg was on the cusp of success with the massive release of her 2012 project Stranger Insights.
In this, the artist created portraits by sifting DNA from the debris of forensic pieces like cigarette butts and gum to create a picture of what these people might look like.
Just then, he got an e-mail from Paper Magazine.
"They were doing an interview with Chelsea Manning while she was in prison and they wanted some sort of portrait that could accompany this piece", Dewey-Hagborg explained at the press presentation of the new exhibition.
At the time, no visitors were allowed, no photographs, so they reached out to Chelsea and asked if she was interested in getting a DNA portrait.
The artist and his imprisoned inspiration became unexpected correspondents, exchanging many letters over a period of two years.
They even released Repressed Images, a cartoon book illustrated by Shoili Kanungo, in which the president forgives Chelsea's sentence and imagines a future where she can see the exhibition in person.
The fact that Obama actually asked for Manning's release a few days after the book was released was a happy coincidence that came in handy after seven years of atrocities in a military prison in Kansas.
As Donald Trump wages war on government leakers and transgender soldiers and finds new, tweetable ways to further fuel the sharp divisions he is asked to fix, there is something profound and powerful about this exhibit that is now opening.
When asked about the strange timing of all this, Dewey-Hagborg said, "Things happen for a reason".
An artist's statement on the gallery wall, with Manning's large-scale signature below it (the dot of the "i" in the last name is inserted with a heart), called for an end to "automatic discrimination" based on gender, race, sexuality and culture.
On the wall, there's his mitochondrial DNA sequence, lots of C's, G's and A's written in lead pencil.
By including 200 letters (or nucleotides in the artist's sophisticated science dictionary), Dewey Hagborg wanted to tell how remarkably similar we all are, at least as biological creatures.
"What I hope people will take away from this is that they don't care about who we are and how open to interpretation the genetic data is, how subjective it is", said Dewey-Hagborg, who is exhibiting his video work Simulated Memories in 2007.
"DNA data can tell many different stories, and these are 30 of them".
The last piece in the one-room exhibition is a page from the aforementioned short comic book.
Here Manning is shown, King Kong-style, leaving with a speaker from the United States Disciplinary Barracks.
It says, "They win when they silence you".
"So never shut up".
The artist from Philadelphia said, "This came directly from a letter he wrote to me".
"I still get a little bit of a tingle when I talk about it".
Manning has not yet seen the exhibition in person (as is quite predictably envisioned in the comic book), but when he does, he will be greeted by masks of his own genetic imitation, which are gathered in the middle of the room like a group of protesters.
Like everything in the exhibition, the genetic haplogroups were written in pencil up to Manning's height (5'2, Manning's height), which was specially made.
Dewey-Hagborg said about portraits, "I used to put them on the walls, but I wanted them to feel like a crowd".
"I wanted it to be perceived as a collective movement, shaped by Chelsea, which was also the movement behind her liberation".
