Creating a comic: The story of a castle in England
In more recent times, the tiny Scotney Castle was featured in a Squeeze music video and was a haven for Margaret Thatcher in the 1970s and 1980s.
But now, inspired by a comic book by Jamie Rhodes, a Yorkshire man with brown hair and a passion for historical documentation, Scotney has witnessed 700 years of turbulent history from his comfortable seat in the Bewl River valley in Kent.
"I find it beautiful to look at the handwriting of someone who's been dead for 300 years", she says, with a sigh.
"What a personal bond it is to hold this letter".
A Castle in England, dating from the Edwardian era to the Middle Ages, each story documents a family living in Scotney, to be painted by a different artist named from the United Kingdom (Isaac Lenkiewicz, Briony May Smith, William Exley, Becky Palmer and Isabel Greenberg).
This is not Rhodes' first book based on an archive: he also wrote the 2014 project Dead Men's Teeth and Other Stories, which he found unexpectedly emotional, inspired by stories in the British Library.
"I even saw a fingerprint on the side of a letter written in the 1700s by a double agent working for King James's supporters", he says.
"That was his thumbprint!
And the letters always smell like wormwood because back then you used to light a fire for the light.
For someone 300 years in the future, that smell makes it feel like he's there.
Oh, I love the archives!"
As a lover of old papers, getting support from the National Trust and Arts Council England and staying in a castle for almost four months ("I've been a little overwhelmed, to be honest, by the warm welcome I received") seems too good.
Rhodes spent his days exploring the "new" Victorian castle, scanning the archives and studying many treasures and antiquities, such as the rattlesnakes' heads mounted on the mansion walls and bottles that had been in the ditches for centuries.
He toured the grounds and ruins of the old castle, talking to keepers, gardeners and sometimes artists who worked on the illustrations of his book.
Then at night he would "drink whiskey and write".
The detailed history of Scotney is relatively unknown, as the National Trust only gained full access when the last heir, Elizabeth Hussey, died in 2006.
When Rhodes arrived ten years later, the staff had only just begun to take over the archives, which he describes as, "For centuries, the aristocrats were saying, 'Oh, throw it in the attic.'"
Diaries, letters from the days of the British Empire, maps that defined the boundaries of who owned what: "You would think land disputes would be boring", says Rhodes, "but there was a willow tree that two families fought over.
Forget about it, guys!"
Some stories in the collection, including The Labourer, who left the newly built castle to take part in the Peasants' Revolt of 1381, use the castle as a springboard to make a broader introduction to English history.
"In this book, The Knights of Kent and Sussex, there is a record of a rebellion at the castle in 1380", says Rhodes.
"The peasant rebellion had started in this area, and I thought a rebellion might be a good starting point.
Maybe the two are connected?"
Other stories are closely linked to the castle's history, such as The Priest, which tells the story of the Darrell family who hid a Jesuit priest for seven years during the English Reformation.
Or The Smuggler, featuring 18th-century smuggler Arthut Darrell, who is thought to have filled a coffin with stones and arranged his own funeral.
The Darrells were Rhodes' most beloved Scotney family: "These gentlemen looked like a lot of crooks, always going into debt and spending money on things they couldn't afford.
In different generations, Darrell men have solved their debt crises by marrying wealthy older women, and I imagine them as a group of handsome men with the art of wooing female heirs".
With his tour of duty at the fort over, Rhodes is looking for other solo writing experiences.
In the Finnish wildlife, he completed a two-week work for a comic about Elämänmäki, the site of a sanatorium in the early 20th century, which has since been recaptured by nature.
But Scotney holds a special place in his heart.
"I was sad to be separated", she says.
"It's like, 'Oh, I have to go now and face my real fucking life.'"
