Red meat, dairy products, and chocolate may alleviate IBS
Red meat and chocolate may sound like a nightmare for your digestive system.
But a new study suggests the opposite: A diet rich in meat-based protein and dairy products may help alleviate symptoms in those suffering from inflammatory bowel disease.
This incurable health condition affects 1.3 million people in the United States and 300,000 in the United Kingdom, causing stomach cramps and bloating, recurrent or bloody diarrhea, weight loss, and extreme fatigue.
Although patients are often advised to skip meat and dairy products to alleviate their symptoms, researchers at the University of Washington found that the protein, the essential amino acid tryptophan, helps develop immune cells that develop a resilient gut.
Dr. Marco Colonna, the lead researcher, said that immune cells patrol the intestines to prevent germs stored in food from sneaking into the body.
Cells that are capable of triggering inflammation are balanced by cells that promote endurance, protecting sensitive tissues from damage.
If the balance shifts too much toward inflammation, it can result in inflammatory bowel disease.
Experiments have shown that mice carrying a specific bacterium in their intestines have developed a type of immune cell that promotes endurance.
And the bacteria need tryptophan, one of the building blocks of the protein, to trigger the cell to emerge.
'We have linked the development of a cell population that promotes resistance to Lactobacillus reuteri, a bacterium that is part of the gut microbiome,' said Professor Colonna.
Mice with more tryptophan in their diet had more of these immune cells".
If the same thing happens in humans, he suggested, a diet rich in L. reuteri and tryptophan could develop a more resilient, less inflammatory gut environment.
While working on a type of immune cell that enhances endurance, postdoctoral researcher Dr. Luisa Cervantes-Barraganwas discovered that one group of mice had these types of cells, but another group of the same species held in a different location did not.
He suspected that the difference was related to the gut microbiome of mice, in other words, the communities of bacteria, viruses and fungi that normally live in the gastrointestinal tract.
So we did a DNA sequencing of the intestines of the mice, and we found that the mice that had immune cells had six types of bacteria, but the mice that didn't have them, they didn't have them.
Mice that were treated in a sterile environment and lacked a gut microbiome and did not develop this type of immune cell were given L. reuteri and immune cells were shown.
To understand how the bacteria affected the immune system, the researchers grew L. reuteri in liquid and then transferred small amounts of this bacterially-free liquid to immature immune cells from mice.
The immune cells became the cells that promote endurance.
The active ingredient was found to be a byproduct of the metabolism of tryptophan, known as indole-3-lactic acid, when purified from the liquid.
When the researchers doubled the amount of tryptophan in the mice's diet, the number of cells increased by about 50 percent, but when the levels of tryptophan were halved, the number of cells fell by half.
Dr. Cervantes-Barragan said that humans have the same cells that promote endurance as mice, and that most of us have L. reuteri in the gastrointestinal tract.
It is not known whether the tryptophan by-products from L. reuteri develop in humans as they do in mice, but disorders in the genes associated with tryptophan have been found in people with inflammatory bowel disease.
He said: "The growth of these cells is probably something we want to encourage because these cells control inflammation in the inner surface of the intestines.
Potentially, in cases where L. reuteri is present, high levels of tryptophan are causing this population to spread".
