The White House parade cost thousands of taxpayers
According to military records released to TIME, the White House's decision last month to fly a Marine helicopter into the grasslands of the South for an organization that promotes American manufacturing cost taxpayers up to $24,000.
When the president boarded, the green and white Sikorsky VH-3D, also known as Marine One, was the focus of the organization's July 17 presentation of American construction programs at the White House.
President Donald Trump, Vice President Mike Pence and senior White House officials toured the products manufactured in all 50 states.
A Connecticut-built helicopter, a yacht from Maine, a fire truck from Wisconsin, and a fork lift from Mississippi were displayed side by side.
According to records from Marine Helicopter Squadron One (HMX-1), the unit in charge of operating the helicopter, the White House War Department requested the helicopter's presence in a separate order (also called FRAGO) just 36 hours before the helicopter landed on the southern grasslands for an "unusual" organization.
The commander of HMX-1, the day before the organization, sent an e-mail to the Vice Commandant of Marine Aviation, who was in charge, saying, "I just wanted to make sure you were aware because this is an unusually high-visibility organization".
The message said the helicopter would arrive on the south lawn around 7 a.m. on July 17 for the 3 p.m. organization and stay there until the lawn was cleared between 6 and 9 p.m.
The note added that if departure from the White House was delayed, a second flight crew would be needed for the return flight due to duty time restrictions.
Unit security personnel were inside the aircraft while the aircraft was on the ground, while the original flight crew was in the helicopter during the organization.
The records provided to TIME make it unclear whether a second flight crew would be necessary.
The Hatch Act prohibits federal employees from using government property for political purposes.
The records show that HMX-1 is investigating whether the organization violated this requirement.
The commander wrote, "A question we asked was whether he violated the Hatch Act, and we were told he did not".
"Looks like you're stuck", the Deputy Commander replied.
The Made in America organization is officially designated by the White House and is not covered by the Hatch Act.
But even official organizations have political implications.
In the organization, the president referred to the health care reform efforts that were underway in the Senate at the time and praised the government's efforts to rein in regulations.
The use of the aircraft, known as Marine One or Air Force One, for political advantage is not new.
Presidents are supposed to use these to travel.
But it's unusual that they're officially requested to be used for a photo opportunity only.
Trump drew attention in February when his presidential plane moved backstage to the first campaign rally in Melbourne Florida, and his Twitter account was filled with messages about his predecessor's use of the presidential plane.
"The White House is excited about the 'Made in America' exhibit, which features products made with American materials by American workers from all 50 states", said Lindsay Walters, deputy press secretary.
The HMX-1 crew frequently makes training flights in the Washington area, and on the south lawn, they practice dropping the President of the United States into the White House with a point-blank range.
While Trump was in Germany for the G-20 summit in early July, HMX-1 made 58 training landings at the White House.
An official said the flight, for the Made in America organization, was considered the training requirement for the flight crew that month.
Unit helicopters flew an additional 11 hours that day for "non-presidential support missions".
The White House said taxpayers didn't charge for any other tricks involved in the organization.
A spokesman for Sikorksky said his company was not involved in arranging the display of the helicopter on the south lawn.
HMX-1 does not keep budget records for presidential flights, and it is difficult to determine the exact expenditures incurred by the organization.
But according to the Department of Defense's hourly rates for fiscal year 2017, the Department of Defense's rate of admission to the VH-3D is $24,340 per flight hour.
Unit logs record the flight time of the aircraft as 30 minutes each way from the Marine Corps Air Facility headquarters in Quantico, Virginia.
The White House claims the actual operating cost of the helicopter is far below that.
"It's very misleading to charge taxpayers based on estimates of the rate of return", Walters said.
"These estimates include the cost of personnel, maintenance and annual costs".
A 2015 RAND study found that the Department of Defense's expense coverage rates do not include personnel costs but include fuel, maintenance and contract costs.
At the time, former White House press secretary Sean Spicer advocated that the helicopter be used for this organization.
Spicer said, "The idea here is to show what's been done in America this week".
"And I know that Sikorsky and the state of Connecticut are very proud of their contributions to our national security, and I suspect that hundreds, if not thousands, of people depend on it.
And I think we're all proud of the helicopters and other military equipment that many Americans, like many Americans, have worked tirelessly to build.
So it's certainly appropriate to bring it up".
It's unclear if Trump interacted with the helicopter while touring the southern grasslands for the organization, but he stepped into the driver's seat of a fire truck.
